# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animal-justice-party-of-finland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2017-finnish-municipal-elections] Municipal elections were held in Finland on 9 April 2017 with advance voting between 29 March and 4 April.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2017-finnish-municipal-elections] The councils in 295 municipalities in Finland (excluding Åland) were elected.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2017-finnish-municipal-elections] Several municipalities altered the size of their councils (mainly because of municipal mergers) before the elections which resulted in reduction of seats available from 9,674 to 8,999.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2017-finnish-municipal-elections] Poll results are listed in the table below in reverse chronological order, showing the most recent first.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2017-finnish-municipal-elections] The highest percentage figure in each poll is displayed in bold, and the background shaded in the leading party's colour.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2017-finnish-municipal-elections] In the instance that there is a tie, then no figure is shaded.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2017-finnish-municipal-elections] The table uses the date the survey's fieldwork was done, as opposed to the date of publication.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2017-finnish-municipal-elections] However, if that date is unknown, the date of publication will be given instead.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2017-finnish-municipal-elections] List includes only polls that were made for the municipal election.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] Parliamentary elections were held in Finland on 14 April 2019.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] For the first time, no party received more than 20% of the vote.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Centre Party, which had been the largest party following the 2015 elections, dropped to fourth place, losing 18 seats and recording its lowest vote share since 1917.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Social Democratic Party saw the biggest gains, winning six more seats and narrowly becoming the largest party for the first time since 1999.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Green League and the Left Alliance also gained five and four seats respectively.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Finns Party and the National Coalition Party gained one seat each, with the Finns Party recovering the seats it had lost in the previous parliament when 21 of its MPs left to form Blue Reform, which failed to win a seat.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Swedish People's Party and the Christian Democrats retained all of their seats that they had won in the previous elections.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Åland Coalition retained their seat in Åland, whilst Harry Harkimo, a former National Coalition MP who founded Movement Now twelve months earlier, was reelected in his constituency, thus giving his own movement its first elected MP.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] Social Democratic Party leader Antti Rinne subsequently formed a coalition government with the Centre Party, Green League, Left Alliance and Swedish People's Party.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] Due to the Centre Party's devastating defeat, outgoing party leader and Prime Minister Juha Sipilä consequently announced that he would continue as the chairman only until the party's next convention in September 2019.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] The incumbent government was formed by a three party center-right coalition, composed of the Centre Party, Finns Party and National Coalition Party.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] On 28 May 2015, the parliament elected Juha Sipilä as prime minister by a vote of 128–62.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] On 10 June 2017, the Finns Party elected Jussi Halla-aho as the new leader of the party, after the long-time leader Timo Soini had decided to step down.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] Following the talks among the three coalition leaders, Sipilä and Minister of Finance Petteri Orpo announced that they would no longer cooperate in a coalition government with the Finns Party.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] The collapse of government was averted on 13 June when twenty MPs defected from the Finns Party's parliamentary group, forming what would eventually become the Blue Reform party.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] One MP (Kike Elomaa) later returned to the Finns Party and another (Kaj Turunen) defected to National Coalition Party, leaving the Blue Reform with 18 and Finns Party with 17 MPs.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] Veera Ruoho furthermore defected to the National Coalition.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] Sipilä's government retained a majority in the Parliament as the Blue Reform continued as a member of the coalition and the Finns Party was moved to the opposition.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] On 8 March 2019, prime minister Sipilä resigned.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] However, that same day president Sauli Niinistö reappointed him as head of a caretaker government.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] According to Sipilä, his government collapsed because of the failure to reach agreement on the controversial health care reform.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] But several Finnish political analysts (Thomas Karv, Teivo Teivainen) interpreted his resignation as a strategic move that could give the coalition parties, Sipilä's Centre Party in particular, more freedom during the election campaign.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] Thus, the Centre Party might be able to revive itself in the polls, in which the party was lagging behind the Social Democrats.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] After the Oulu child sexual exploitation scandal, support for the anti-immigration Finns Party surged from around 9% in late 2018 to 17.5% by the election.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Social Democrats proposed raising taxes to fund the country's welfare system.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] The election saw "an unusual level of aggression on the campaign trail", especially considering "attacks on politicians are rare in Finland".
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] In late March, a man struck Left Alliance candidate Suldaan Said Ahmed in the chest while calling him an infidel and pedophile a day after a man wearing logos of far-right anti-immigrant group Soldiers of Odin attempted to attack Foreign Minister Timo Soini of the Blue Party.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] The 200 members of the Eduskunta were elected using proportional representation in 13 multi-member constituencies, with seats allocated according to the D'Hondt method.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] The number of elected representatives is proportional to the population in the district six months prior to the elections. Åland has single member electoral district and its own party system.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] Compared to the previous election in 2015, one seat was reallocated from Savo-Karelia to Uusimaa.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] (5 poll average of finnish opinion polls from April 2015 to the election 2019.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] Voter turnout was 72%, the highest since 1987.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] The highest turnout was in the Helsinki constituency, where the turnout was 78%.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] The lowest was in Savo-Karelia constituency at 67% and Åland constituency at 60%.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] Women had a slightly higher turnout of 74% compared for men who had a turnout of 71%.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] During election debates, the Social Democrats, the National Coalition Party, Green League, Left Alliance, and the Swedish People's Party stated that they were interested in joining a coalition that does not include the Finns Party.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] Despite being ruled-out by five parties, Finns Party chairman Jussi Halla-aho said that all parties should show responsibility when forming a coalition.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] He said the most responsible way to form a coalition is to include the Finns Party.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] Two weeks later, SDP chairman Antti Rinne, who was expected to lead the government, sent a questionnaire to each of the other parties, to assess their positions on various topics such as basic income, collective bargaining, climate change or health care reform.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] Based on the answers and initial talks with all parties, Rinne announced that he would negotiate forming a government with Centre Party, Green League, Left Alliance and Swedish People's Party.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2019-finnish-parliamentary-election] The negotiations were ultimately successful, and the Rinne Cabinet was formally inaugurated on 6 June.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2021-finnish-municipal-elections] Second largest party by vote percentage.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2021-finnish-municipal-elections] Largest party by seats in the municipality council.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2021-finnish-municipal-elections] Municipal elections were held in Finland on 13 June 2021 after being rescheduled from 18 April due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2021-finnish-municipal-elections] The last municipal elections were held in 2017 and were won by the National Coalition Party with a 20.7 percent share of the votes.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2021-finnish-municipal-elections] Most parties, such as the Social Democratic Party, Centre Party, Green League, and the Left Alliance showed a decline in their vote share and council seats.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2021-finnish-municipal-elections] The National Coalition Party had a small increase, while the biggest winner was the Finns Party, who saw a major increase in vote share and council seats.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2021-finnish-municipal-elections] The 14.5% they received is the highest vote share in municipal elections since the party's foundation.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2021-finnish-municipal-elections] The party is now the largest group on at least six councils: in Hamina, Orimattila, Kihniö, Ylöjärvi, Kankaanpää and Hämeenkyrö.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Parliamentary elections were held in Finland on 2 April 2023 to elect members of the Parliament of Finland.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Following the 2019 election, the Social Democratic Party (SDP) formed a governing coalition with the Centre Party, Greens, Left Alliance, and the Swedish People's Party, with Antti Rinne serving as the prime minister of Finland.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Later that year, Rinne was involved in a political scandal regarding the Finnish postal service, after which he resigned and was succeeded by Sanna Marin.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Marin's government focused on issues regarding climate change, while her government also faced the COVID-19 pandemic and the Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] The invasion prompted her to announce that Finland would submit its candidacy to join NATO, which it did in May 2022.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Issues regarding the economy, the budget deficit, climate change, and education were discussed during the campaign period.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] The election programs or the opposition National Coalition Party (NCP) and Finns Party (Finns) called for budget cuts and austerity to balance the budget, while the SDP's election program focused on economic growth through investments in employment and education.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Marin supported more education and public health spending, while the NCP called for balancing the budget, reducing spending on unemployment and housing benefits, and constructing more nuclear plants.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Finns campaigned on an anti-immigration and anti-European Union platform, while the Greens focused on issues regarding mental health and universal basic income.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Centre Party campaigned on regional politics.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] The National Coalition Party won the election with 20.8% of the national popular vote, winning 48 seats in parliament, the third-highest result in the party's history.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Finns Party came in a close second place with the ruling Social Democratic Party of Finland under Prime Minister Marin in third place.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] The National Coalition Party then formed a coalition with the Finns Party, the Swedish People's Party, and the Christian Democrats, with Petteri Orpo as prime minister.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] For the first time in Finland's history, the Centre Party did not win a plurality of votes in any regional voting districts.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Five government parties and four opposition parties finished with parliamentary seats split at 100–100.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] This was the first time since 1983 that the top-three finishing parties did not lose a percentage share of votes.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] The previous parliamentary election, held in April 2019, saw the Social Democratic Party place first, winning 17.7% of the popular vote, followed by the Finns Party and the National Coalition Party, who won 17.5% and 17% of the popular vote, respectively.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Centre Party of the outgoing prime minister Juha Sipilä placed fourth, winning 13.8% of the popular vote, while the Green League and the Left Alliance received more votes than in the preceding election.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] In June 2019, after several months of negotiations, the SDP, led by Rinne, formed a government, bringing the Centre Party, Green League, Left Alliance, and the Swedish People's Party into the government.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] In late 2019, a political scandal regarding the Finnish postal service broke out.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Sirpa Paatero, the minister of local government and ownership steering, was accused of being aware of, and hiding from members of the Parliament of Finland, the postal service's project to change the status of a large number of its workers to a lower-paying contract.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Paatero resigned in November 2019, after which Rinne was also accused of knowing of the postal service's plan.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Centre Party then left the government, which led Rinne to announce his resignation as prime minister and leader of the SDP in December 2019.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] He was succeeded by Sanna Marin, who, at 34, became the world's youngest serving prime minister after being sworn into office in December 2019.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Marin Cabinet announced they would combat climate change, protect the environment, and reduce social and economic inequalities.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Her government also adopted a program that would aim to make Finland carbon-neutral by 2035, by reducing greenhouse gas emissions and increasing the production of renewable energy.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Following the outbreak of the COVID-19 pandemic in Finland, Marin's management of the pandemic benefited her party, which caused her to rise in opinion polls, with her personal favourable opinion rating reaching 85%.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] The SDP was surpassed by the Finns Party in opinion polls after April 2021, with the National Coalition Party becoming the most popular by July 2021.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Following the beginning of the Russian invasion of Ukraine, Marin took a firm line against Russia and Vladimir Putin, breaking Finland's historical military neutrality by announcing Finland's NATO candidacy.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Finland officially submitted its candidacy in May 2022.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Its path to join NATO was formalized in March 2023, when Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, the president of Turkey, formally signed and approved the decision to ratify Finland's NATO membership.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Turkey was the last NATO member to ratify the decision.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] The 200 members of the Parliament of Finland (*Eduskunta*, *Riksdagen*) were elected using open list, proportional representation in 13 multi-member electoral districts, with seats allocated according to the D'Hondt method.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] The number of elected representatives is proportional to the population in the district six months prior to the elections. Åland has a single-member electoral district and its own party system.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Every citizen who is at least 18 years old has the right to vote.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Voters also had the option to vote either during the advance voting period, from March 22 to 28 March 2023, or on election day.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] The table below lists parties and independent candidates that contested the 2023 Finnish parliamentary election.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Election Information and Results Service announced that 2,424 candidates in total registered to take part in the election.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Yle cited government borrowing, sustainability of public finances, climate change, and educational decline as main issues during the electoral campaign.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Paul Kirby of BBC News noted that the Russian invasion of Ukraine has had "little campaign impact", and added that the campaign was instead concentrated on issues regarding the economy.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Deutsche Welle cited a shortage of workers as a key issue, while the Associated Press mentioned that issues regarding the economy, climate change, education, and social benefits were discussed during the campaign.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Markku Jokisipilä, an assistant professor at the University of Turku, said that in the debates, Marin has "stood out vigorously".
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] He added that the Finns Party had the strongest social media presence.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Teivo Teivainen, a professor at the University of Helsinki, said that opponents of the SDP see the main problem as public spending.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] News agencies described the election as a close race between the SDP, National Coalition Party, and the Finns Party.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Finns Party, which campaigned on an anti-immigration and anti-European Union (EU) platform, cited as their priority cutting immigration from non-EU countries.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Petteri Orpo, the leader of the National Coalition Party, campaigned on reducing spending on unemployment and housing benefits.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] While campaigning, Orpo stated his support for economic growth, balancing the public economy, "building up NATO-Finland", and constructing more nuclear plants.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Riikka Purra, the leader of the Finns Party, called for austerity, and said that "we also want to tighten up our attitude towards the European Union." She added that the Finns Party would delay the carbon neutrality target that was introduced by Marin's government.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] The National Coalition Party agreed with Marin's position on carbon neutrality.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Green League's campaign was focused on mental health services and universal basic income.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] During the advance voting period, 40% of eligible voters cast their ballots, the highest since the introduction of advance voting.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Voting stations on April 2 were opened from 9:00 (UTC+03:00) a.m. to 8:00 pm.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] There were 4,277,487 citizens who had the right to vote in the election.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Before the election, the Social Democratic Party, Green League, and the Left Alliance ruled out joining a coalition that involved the Finns Party.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Swedish People's Party similarly stated that they were unlikely to align with the Finns but did not rule the possibility out completely.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] According to Swedish People's Party leader Anna-Maja Henriksson, her party wanted to see how government talks would go before making a final decision.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Left Alliance also stated that they were not ready to enter a coalition that involved the National Coalition Party.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] National Coalition Party leader Petteri Orpo said he was keeping his options open.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] News agencies predicted that if his party was the largest, he would need to team up with the Finns Party or the Social Democratic Party, along with smaller parties, to get a majority.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] After the immediate results of the election, the incumbent coalition did not have an absolute majority in parliament.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] The results showed that Orpo had to face difficult options, as his party differed from the Finns on immigration, climate, and EU membership status.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Additionally, forming a coalition with them was said to be difficult because some parties had already ruled out a coalition with the Finns.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] On the other hand, he vowed to replace the economic policy of the Social Democrats.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] At that point, it was widely anticipated that the Centre Party, Green League, and Left Alliance would prefer to go into opposition rather than join a new coalition.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] This left the Swedish People's Party and Christian Democrats, which held their ground, as likely coalition partners.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] The media reported that Orpo was leaning towards talks with the Finns Party first, but also that he was sending out a questionnaire to each of the other parties to assess their positions on various topics.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] On 4 April 2023, the leader of the Social Democratic Party, Sanna Marin, announced that she had resigned as chairwoman of her party, but remained a lawmaker in parliament.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Centre Party leader Annika Saarikko confirmed that the Centre Party's place was in the opposition following the party's election losses.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Green League party leader Maria Ohisalo made similar statements, citing monetary cuts to education, insufficiently countering climate change, and nature loss as major concerns.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Swedish People's Party leader Anna-Maja Henriksson said she did not rule out joining a coalition with the Finns Party, but stated that she opposed the policies and values that the Finns pursue.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Christian Democratic leader Sari Essayah said she was open to joining a coalition led by the National Coalition if the coalition agreed to implement major structural reforms in the labour markets and social security system.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Based on the answers and initial talks with all parties, Orpo announced that he would negotiate forming a government with the Finns Party, Swedish People's Party, and the Christian Democrats.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] Petteri Orpo announced on 15 June that the four parties had agreed to establish a four-party coalition government, which would include the far-right Finns Party.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] The composition of the government, the assignment of nineteen ministerial posts, was announced on 17 June.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2023-finnish-parliamentary-election] The National Coalition received eight posts, the Finns Party seven, and the Swedish People's Party three, with the remaining one going to the Christian Democrats.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2025-finnish-municipal-elections] The **2025 Finnish municipal elections** were held on 13 April 2025, the same day as the county elections.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2025-finnish-municipal-elections] On that day, the representatives for the 308 municipal councils were elected.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2025-finnish-municipal-elections] A poll by the Association of Finnish Local and Regional Authorities suggested that 80 percent of people in Finland planned to vote in the 2025 elections.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2025-finnish-municipal-elections] The right to vote in municipal elections is determined by the municipality in which a person is registered fifty-one days before the election.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2025-finnish-municipal-elections] The center-left SDP saw major gains in the election, while the right-wing populist Finns Party saw major losses.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2025-finnish-municipal-elections] It was reported that the Finns party lost votes due to its government support for austerity, while the voters of the center-right NCP approve of the government policy.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2025-finnish-municipal-elections] This was the first time SDP topped the polls in municipal elections since the 2004 elections.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2025-finnish-municipal-elections] In the capital city of Helsinki, the National Coalition narrowly managed to retain their top spot despite a dramatic increase in voting share for the SDP.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2025-finnish-municipal-elections] The SDP managed to tie the National Coalition in seat number despite finishing with a slightly lower percentage of the vote.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2025-finnish-municipal-elections] In the second largest city of Tampere, the SDP retained the top spot and increased its lead over second place National Coalition after a near-tie in the last election.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2025-finnish-municipal-elections] The Finns Party lost almost half of their votes.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/2025-finnish-municipal-elections] As a function of their collapse all other major parties were able to increase their vote share.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/animal-justice-party-of-finland] According to the party's manifesto, its main goal is to make Finland "a society where humans and other animals are offered equal rights to a full life and a secure future", and to promote fair treatment of all animals.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/animal-justice-party-of-finland] The party supports veganism, arguing that eating meat cannot be considered a private preference because it threatens the environment and ecosystems on Earth.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/animal-justice-party-of-finland] The EOP states that "the meat norm and the habits associated with it must be dismantled".
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/animal-justice-party-of-finland] It argues that "moving to a vegan society is the lifeblood of our future", and sees veganism as not only a moral necessity, but also a way to abolish the 'culture of violence' produced by the exploitation and commodification of animals.
[src:animal-justice-party-of-finland/animal-justice-party-of-finland] Along with other parties of the Animal Politics EU, the EOP has also adopted a left-wing ideology, which includes criticism of capitalism and globalization, and supporting the expansion of welfare state.
